Remove the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}(halved lengthways and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press). Roughly chop the @parsley{5%g}(roughly chopped; stalks and all).

Boil @water{1%L} in a #pot{} for the stock. Add @vegetable stock{1%sachet} to the water, bring to the boil and stir to dissolve. Simmer on low heat.

Place a (separate) #large pot{} over medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Once oil is hot, add @chorizo{100%g} and cook until golden, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the leek and fry until softened, another ~{5%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @risotto rice{225%g} to the pot with the chorizo. Cook over medium-low heat until the edges of the rice are translucent, stirring occasionally, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @red wine vinegar{1%sachet}, stir and allow to evaporate, about ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in a ladle of your stock. When the stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle. Keep the pot on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time.

The cooking time should take ~{25-30%minutes} and your risotto is done when the rice is al dente—cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

When the risotto has 3 mins left, stir the @sugar snap peas{150%g}(washed) through. Cook for the remaining time until just tender.

Once cooked, remove the risotto from the heat. Stir in some @?butter{to taste}, half the parsley and three-quarters of the @grated Italian style hard cheese{50%g}.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Serve your risotto in #deep bowls{} with the remaining cheese and parsley scattered on top.

> Risotto is a meal that requires a little bit of patience to prepare. But the moment you take your first bite of this creamy and decadent dish you'll realise it was well worth the wait!